text.text: Where big chunks of metal and glass scrape the sky, where medium-sized sacks of flesh crush big-time bucks, where small-fry matters like splitting the bill are a distant myth. This is a city within a city, a contained corporate carnival thatâ€™s often a mystery to the layman. And so we got curious... Canary Wharf, prepare yourself.
Best for... a raw fish splash out

tip.text:
What would you expect from a Japanese-Danish collaboration? Minimalism, style and efficiency - and it wouldnâ€™t be cheap. This slick and sexy sushi joint is just that, perfect for a fast and furious business lunch. Evenings are more ambient and relaxed, so grab one of the high tables and observe the bustle of the room from a vantage point.

Yes, the food is absolutely stunning but it will set you back a penny - the recommended sharing platter for newcomers, The Upgrade, is going for Â£65 between two - and ainâ€™t exactly a tummy filler. Options include 14 set menus, combining both hot and cold dishes, as well as the Ã  la carte option. Smash your piggy bank, treat yourself and go all out if youâ€™re feeling brave.

text.html: So youâ€™ve got your slick suit, you look damn good and you need somewhere equally snazzy to break bread with your peers. This is the spot. Sticks â€˜nâ€™ Sushi has been smashing it in Copenhagen for years now and itâ€™s understandable. Chow down and take in the gorgeous murals painted on the walls by a Danish artist during service. Warning: food does not come cheap here.

tip.text:
This is some real nerdy, artisan coffee stuff. The espresso recipe here is done by weight so if yours looks slightly short then donâ€™t fret - every bean is different and requires treating as such. Notes source their beans from independent suppliers in the likes of Ethiopia and Kenya, always prioritising quality.

This spot is busiest either side of lunch when the office walls start closing in, and at around 4 or 5 Notes transforms into a wine bar complete with full table service. You can expect a well travelled selection of old and new world wines to compliment simple evening plates, while jazz nights have been thrown in the past so be sure to watch this space.

text.html: Whatâ€™s a day in the office without that welcome escape for a coffee fix? Heck, Notes has queues around the block in the summer so you know the stuff is ace. The staff probe customers about preferences so they can whip you up the perfect cup of joe. Folk have been known to get too absorbed in the movie playing on the mini-projector and miss their orders being called - donâ€™t let that be you.

Best for... some Indian soul food

tip.text: Inspired by the coastal drinking dens of India, Chai Ki dishes up Indian soul food in a slick setting. After checking out the new Crossrail Roof Gardens upstairs, we treated ourselves to buttermilk pancakes (made with 'chaas' buttermilk) and the full Nashta - basically a full English made a whole lot more interesting. The fragrant and yoghurty mango Shrikand was also bloody delightful. Along with a cracking brunch, Chai-Ki offer sharing plates, cocktails and even a house-infused beer. Try it if you're feeling, erm ballsy.

tip.text:
Brass features heavily in this retro-feeling picturehouse. The remains of a James Bond exhibition include a model Aston Martin DB5 and series of classic Bond photos, and the suave interior of this Everyman make it feel like the sort of place 007 might catch a flick of himself.

Warning: there are only a few daily showings, an unfortunate consequence of existing in banker-central - as you can expect, however, it does get busy for post-work features. This ainâ€™t no Odeon either: hot food options include pizzas and proper hot dogs, while beers, wines and cocktails are all on offer for you thirsty fish. Sweeter treats include sundaes and milkshakes (P.S. the oreo one is available but not on the menu so be sure to ask!).

text.text: Thereâ€™s no better way of winding down and switching off after a long dayâ€™s slog bringing home the bacon than sitting in a dark room and having a big screen flash stuff at you. Even better when the cinema in question is a proper classy affair offering up the likes of pizzas, milkshakes and sundaes. The only drawback here is the limited number of daily viewings so be sure to plan ahead.
Best for... a blast from the past

tip.text:
A pub has occupied this historic site for over 250 years, and while the current building may not date so far back thereâ€™s still plenty of history to be discovered at The Gun. A prime example of this is The River Room upstairs, where Lord Nelson used get a little bit-on-the-side with Lady Emma. The whole site has a time-soaked rickety feel, with sweeping Thames views and walls decorated with guns, stuffed animals and paintings of warships.

On the seasonal menu expect British classics - we particularly liked the monkfish cheeks followed by slow-cooked shoulder of Devonshire Kid. For your liver: local beers, a pint of Jugged Hare coming in at Â£3.80.

text.text: Time for a history lesson: this gastro pub backing onto the Thames boasts plenty of character and many a tale. Once upon a time the back door was left open nightly so sailors could pop by in the night, pour themselves a pint and leave a penny on the bar. Also, Nelson used to conduct affairs upstairs - naughty. Located in a residential area in Canary Wharf, this is a welcome respite from skyscraper city.
Best for... feeling like you're not in Canary Wharf

tip.text: Waging war on weak, tasteless coffee, these skilled baristas will make sure you keep coming back. Not in the scary way, more in the sense that you'll enjoy their coffee, and caffeine is addictive, so you might want more of their delicious brand of it. Anyway, you can also get your hands on cakes and treats here.

tip.text:
If you were wondering where bankers brunch and suits supper then weâ€™ve found the place. Head Chef Daniel McGarey (formerly of Michelin star restaurant Galvin at Windows) is working all kinds of modern European wonders in the kitchen. How does Anjou pigeon with saffron cous cous and seared foie grois sound? Or grilled salmon and lobster crushed potatoes? Yep, divine. And youâ€™ve got a choice of 400 (!) wines to choose from.

Donâ€™t let the swanky vibes make you feel too pedestrian for this spot - thereâ€™s a bottomless bubbles brunch on Saturdays and set menus come as kind as Â£35 for a 3 course meal. Grab a window seat in the classy leather bar, sip on a cocktail and tell yourself you fit right in.

text.text: The ultimate fine-dining City experience has got to be found at Plateau, one of Canary Wharf's most celebrated corporate eateries. Expect fancy modern European nosh with a noticeable french influence and smashing cocktails. What else would you expect from a swanky, top floor restaurant overlooking the likes of HSBC and JP Morgan? It probably goes without saying but weâ€™d recommend scrubbing up before showing face here.
Best for... a tie-loosening knees up

tip.text:
This weird and wonderful speakeasy is a mighty welcome breath of fresh air in a somewhat stuffy, straight-laced part of town. Pop through the secret door downstairs in The Breakfast Club and find yourself in a red-lit purgatory, just like something out of Twin Peaks. Enter the Dr.â€™s Olde Towne Tavern.

There is one rule and one rule only here: no ties. This will actually be enforced so donâ€™t bother stepping through that door if youâ€™re too uptight. Once youâ€™re kicking back sans neckwear, allow the charming mixologists to relax your body further. Cocktails! These lot specialise in whiskey drinks (the whiskey sour with egg whites is a delight). Also: draught lager comes in schooners (â…” pint). DJs spin party tracks on Thursdays and Fridays, including resident mixologist Mowgli.

text.text: This has to be the most fun spot in Canary Wharf. No ties whatsoever are allowed and the staff arenâ€™t averse to killing the music and starting a whole-room chant to make one individual loosen up. Lethal cocktails are the Dr.â€™s orders and the barmen are a good laugh so good times are likely to roll. Thereâ€™s even a resident DJ who dresses up as Kluger himself - classic.
